Study Title: Understanding the Issue Selection Activities to Contribute to Open Source Software and Strategies to help newcomers onboarding.

Researchers: Marco A. Gerosa, PhD (Northern Arizona University), Igor Steinmacher, PhD (Northern Arizona University),  Igor Wiese, PhD (UTFPR), Fabio Santos, MSc. 

Purpose: Thank you for participating in the survey. The purpose of this research study is to evaluate the process of onboarding newcomers to a project and to understand how to make onboarding easier for the newcomers to a project. Parts of the results of the study will be used to help a student researchers’ thesis or dissertation completion. This study is funded by the National Science Foundation.

Please fill out the short survey which may take about 7 minutes and we will raffle several $25 gift-cards. You will be asked if you want to be included in the raffle upon completion of our survey. To be included in the raffle, you need to provide your e-mail address (which will be used only for the raffle). 

Confidentiality: The security and confidentiality of information collected from you online cannot be guaranteed. Confidentiality will be kept to the extent permitted by the technology being used. Information collected online can be intercepted, corrupted, lost, destroyed, arrive late or incomplete or contain viruses.


Voluntary: Participation in this study is voluntary. You are free to decide not to participate or to withdraw at any time. You can skip questions you prefer not to answer. 

Study contacts: If you have any questions about this research project, please contact: ‘anita.sarma@oregonstate.edu'. If you have questions about your rights or welfare as a participant, please contact the Oregon State University Institutional Review Board (IRB) Office, at (541) 737-8008 or by email at IRB@oregonstate.edu. 



For questions, concerns, or complaints about the study, you may contact,  Fabio Santos .

Q57:
Label the Issues: Create labels to show relevant information that helps new contributors to be aware of the skills, for example:

- Who to contact.

- Related documentation.

- APIs, languages used or other skills.

- First steps to address the issue.

- Issue target (staff, manager, etc.).

- Issue size.
Q59: Improve the process:  Facilitate the contribution process, showing the path to be followed and providing enough detail problems.- Provide details about the issue when writing it. - Describe the process to be followed by contributors and project maintainers.
Q99:
Support newcomers:  Create a structure to facilitate the onboarding, offer guidance and provide adequate issues. - Direct contributors to the issues. Prepare or choose a group of issues for new contributors.- Do a survey to get to know the new contributor better.
- Welcome the new contributor, knowing their skills and motivation.
Q60:
Have good documentation: Create a variety of documentation to cover crucial aspects of the project.- Help new contributors find technical resources by sharing content. 

- Create introductory documentation,  such as getting started, tutorials to cover critical aspects of the project's architecture and technology, a README and documentation to cover code standards. 

- Create conventions for coders to help with maintenance.
Q61:
Have good communication: Keep the communication flowing by using channels and answering their questions. 
- Provide feedback and maintain communication with new contributors.

- Guide new contributors by answering questions and staying in touch. 

- Have communication channels where new contributors can follow and learn about the project and ask questions.
Q62: Improve project quality: Organize the project to better manage it.- Organize the code into modules, taking inventory of code and libraries- Find out which topics and skills are related to each module. - Create unit tests to help contributors test code. - Get metrics from your code to understand its characteristics to know which APIs are used in your modules, for example.- Create a management structure with a group of maintainers or experienced contributors to help new contributors.
Q63: Organize the issues: Manage issues properly.  - Identify the type of issue to help new contributors find a task, and have templates for formatting problem data. - Use similar issues to indicate how similar tasks were solved. - Consolidate duplicate issues and divide issues into smaller subtasks.- Get information about stakeholders affected by the issue to help prioritize or ask questions.

Q66: Understand the issue Read the issue data looking for crucial information. - Read the problem information carefully.- Search for meaningful words (class names, key words etc) that have relevant meaning to solve the issue. - Look for similar issues to see how they were resolved. - Find out the type of problem. Categorize it and understand the type of issue.- See the labels for more brief information about the problem.
Q98: Feel confident to contribute: Stay in touch with the community and actively participate in channels.- Talk to contributors and maintainers to get some guidance and ask questions to get rid of doubts. - Stay in contact with the community to learn about the project and the role of people.
Q67: Setup environment: Run the application and create the development environment.- Learn about the technical details, version and functionality of the project. - Know which tools and program languages ​​are used to run the project. - Run the project. - Understand how to reproduce the error and the feasibility of doing so. - Take the necessary steps to verify the reported error.
Q68:
Understand the Context: Identify the project goals, components. Search for the code related to the issue and understand it.- Understand the general objectives of the application. 

- Identify the main components and the relationship between them and the underlying architecture information provided by folder organization.

- Understand what the code should be doing. Limit your analysis to one code region and keep your work in small places by analyzing inputs and outputs. 

- Know the sequence of function or method calls, libraries and other possible dependencies affected by any updates or affected by the issue. 

- Check the information present in the configuration files and possible correlations with the problem. 

- Check the scope of variables, classes, objects, and other identifiers and understand their roles in execution.
Q69:
Understand what needs to be changed: Debug the code and identify a possible update.- Be aware of which debugging tools are needed. 

- Run debugging. Understand what the cause of the bug is and possible solutions. 

- Check what is being created as output by the application and look for possible correlations with the problem. 

- Change existing parameter values ​​to assess how they might impact the problem.

Q64: Specifically to help new people to contribute with the community is nice to participate into contributions events like “hacktoberfest”. These events reward people thinking to jump into the open source and is a nice way in, also they usually provide a guideline for maintainers with recommendations of how provide a more welcoming project for other developers.
Q72: Bad organized issues will make new people Gil insecure because they will have difficulties to find what they can do to help. Bad labels will have a similar effect, a common label that help a lot new developers is the “good first issue”, so when someone see’s it they will be more confident to work on it, and them evolving to more complex issues later. Process is also something that can be vary overwhelming. For instance if in order to open a pull-request you add a gpg key validation it’s nice to add this in a contributor guide upfront, also make a stable pipeline to test and ensure that the new pull-requests don’t break anything. Project quality is also important, no one wants to work in a confusing code or a bad tested one. Documentations is always important to help people out, but in this context I believe that is a nice to have but not fundamental, same goes for good communication, usually people only uses the issue to talk about the project, some fancy ones with a big user base like ISH app or Golang have a discord or slack server where people can go and talk about suggestions or problems they are facing but in my experience the communication regarding issues stays on the issue it self. For support new comers I believe a guide file is enough to explain the basics of the project and the  contribution process
